# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bisimulation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] In theoretical computer science, a **bisimulation** is a binary relation between state transition systems, associating systems that behave in the same way in that one system simulates the other and vice versa.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Intuitively two systems are bisimilar if they, assuming we view them as playing a *game* according to some rules, match each other's moves.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] In this sense, each of the systems cannot be distinguished from the other by an observer.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] From this follows that the symmetric closure of a bisimulation is a bisimulation, and that each symmetric simulation is a bisimulation.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Thus some authors define bisimulation as a symmetric simulation.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Given two states p and q in S, p is **bisimilar** to q, written $p\,\sim \,q$ , if and only if there is a bisimulation R such that $(p,q)\in R$ .
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] This means that the bisimilarity relation ∼ is the union of all bisimulations: $(p,q)\in \,\sim \,$ precisely when $(p,q)\in R$ for some bisimulation R.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] The set of bisimulations is closed under union; therefore, the bisimilarity relation is itself a bisimulation.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Since it is the union of all bisimulations, it is the unique largest bisimulation.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Bisimulations are also closed under reflexive, symmetric, and transitive closure; therefore, the largest bisimulation must be reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] From this follows that the largest bisimulation—bisimilarity—is an equivalence relation.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Bisimulation can be defined in terms of composition of relations as follows.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] This definition, and the associated treatment of bisimilarity, can be interpreted in any involutive quantale.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Bisimilarity can also be defined in order-theoretical fashion, in terms of fixpoint theory, more precisely as the greatest fixed point of a certain function defined below.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Bisimilarity is then defined to be the greatest fixed point of F .
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Bisimulation can also be thought of in terms of a game between two players: attacker and defender.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] "Attacker" goes first and may choose any valid transition, $\lambda$ , from $(p,q)$ .
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] The "Defender" must then attempt to match that transition, $\lambda$ from either $(p',q)$ or $(p,q')$ depending on the attacker's move.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] By the above definition the system is a bisimulation if and only if there exists a winning strategy for the defender.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] A bisimulation for state transition systems is a special case of coalgebraic bisimulation for the type of covariant powerset functor.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] commutes, i.e. for $i=1,2$ , the equations $\xi _{\rightarrow }\circ \pi _{i}={\mathcal {P}}(\Lambda \times \pi _{i})\circ \gamma$ hold where $\xi _{\rightarrow }$ is the functional representation of $(S,\Lambda ,\rightarrow )$ .
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] In special contexts the notion of bisimulation is sometimes refined by adding additional requirements or constraints.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] An example is that of stutter bisimulation, in which one transition of one system may be matched with multiple transitions of the other, provided that the intermediate states are equivalent to the starting state ("stutters").
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] This is closely related to the notion of bisimulation "up to" a relation.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Typically, if the state transition system gives the operational semantics of a programming language, then the precise definition of bisimulation will be specific to the restrictions of the programming language.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Therefore, in general, there may be more than one kind of bisimulation (respectively bisimilarity) relationship depending on the context.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Since Kripke models are a special case of (labelled) state transition systems, bisimulation is also a topic in modal logic.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] In fact, modal logic is the fragment of first-order logic invariant under bisimulation (van Benthem's theorem).
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] Checking that two finite transition systems are bisimilar can be done in polynomial time.
[src:bisimulation/bisimulation] The fastest algorithms are quasilinear time using partition refinement through a reduction to the coarsest partition problem.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] In mathematics, an **equivalence relation** is a binary relation that is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The equipollence relation between line segments in geometry is a common example of an equivalence relation.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] A simpler example is numerical equality.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Any number a is equal to itself (reflexive).
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Each equivalence relation provides a partition of the underlying set into disjoint equivalence classes.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Two elements of the given set are equivalent to each other if and only if they belong to the same equivalence class.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Non-equivalence may be written " $a\not \sim b$ " or " $a\not \equiv b$ ".
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] A binary relation $\,\sim \,$ on a set X is said to be an equivalence relation if it is reflexive, symmetric and transitive.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] X together with the relation $\,\sim \,$ is called a setoid.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] In relational algebra, if $R\subseteq X\times Y$ and $S\subseteq Y\times Z$ are relations, then the composite relation $SR\subseteq X\times Z$ is defined so that $x\,SR\,z$ if and only if there is a $y\in Y$ such that $x\,R\,y$ and $y\,S\,z$ .
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] This definition is a generalisation of the definition of functional composition.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The set of all equivalence classes for R is $\{\{a\},\{b,c\}\}.$ This set is a partition of the set X .
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] It is also called the quotient set of X by R .
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The latter case with the function f can be expressed by a commutative triangle.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Some authors use "compatible with $\,\sim$ " or just "respects $\,\sim$ " instead of "invariant under $\,\sim$ ".
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] More generally, a function may map equivalent arguments (under an equivalence relation $\,\sim _{A}$ ) to equivalent values (under an equivalence relation $\,\sim _{B}$ ).
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Let $a,b\in X$ , and $\sim$ be an equivalence relation.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] A subset Y of X such that $a\sim b$ holds for all a and b in Y , and never for a in Y and b outside Y , is called an *equivalence class* of X by $\sim$ .
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Let $[a]:=\{x\in X:a\sim x\}$ denote the equivalence class to which a belongs.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] All elements of X equivalent to each other are also elements of the same equivalence class.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The set of all equivalence classes of X by $\sim ,$ denoted $X/{\mathord {\sim }}:=\{[x]:x\in X\},$ is the *quotient set* of X by $\sim .$ If X is a topological space, there is a natural way of transforming $X/\sim$ into a topological space; see *Quotient space* for the details.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The **equivalence kernel** of a function f is the equivalence relation ~ defined by $x\sim y{\text{ if and only if }}f(x)=f(y).$ The equivalence kernel of an injection is the identity relation.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] A *partition* of *X* is a set *P* of nonempty subsets of *X*, such that every element of *X* is an element of a single element of *P*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Each element of *P* is a *cell* of the partition.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Moreover, the elements of *P* are pairwise disjoint and their union is *X*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Let *X* be a finite set with *n* elements.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] In both cases, the cells of the partition of *X* are the equivalence classes of *X* by ~.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Since each element of *X* belongs to a unique cell of any partition of *X*, and since each cell of the partition is identical to an equivalence class of *X* by ~, each element of *X* belongs to a unique equivalence class of *X* by ~.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Thus there is a natural bijection between the set of all equivalence relations on *X* and the set of all partitions of *X*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] If $\sim$ and $\approx$ are two equivalence relations on the same set S , and $a\sim b$ implies $a\approx b$ for all $a,b\in S,$ then $\approx$ is said to be a **coarser** relation than $\sim$ , and $\sim$ is a **finer** relation than $\approx$ .
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The equality equivalence relation is the finest equivalence relation on any set, while the universal relation, which relates all pairs of elements, is the coarsest.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The relation " $\sim$ is finer than $\approx$ " on the collection of all equivalence relations on a fixed set is itself a partial order relation, which makes the collection a geometric lattice.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The equivalence relation generated in this manner can be trivial.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Much of mathematics is grounded in the study of equivalences, and order relations.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Lattice theory captures the mathematical structure of order relations.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Even though equivalence relations are as ubiquitous in mathematics as order relations, the algebraic structure of equivalences is not as well known as that of orders.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The former structure draws primarily on group theory and, to a lesser extent, on the theory of lattices, categories, and groupoids.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Just as order relations are grounded in ordered sets, sets closed under pairwise supremum and infimum, equivalence relations are grounded in partitioned sets, which are sets closed under bijections that preserve partition structure.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Since all such bijections map an equivalence class onto itself, such bijections are also known as permutations.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Hence permutation groups (also known as transformation groups) and the related notion of orbit shed light on the mathematical structure of equivalence relations.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Let '~' denote an equivalence relation over some nonempty set *A*, called the universe or underlying set.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] In sum, given an equivalence relation ~ over *A*, there exists a transformation group *G* over *A* whose orbits are the equivalence classes of *A* under ~.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] This transformation group characterisation of equivalence relations differs fundamentally from the way lattices characterize order relations.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The arguments of the lattice theory operations meet and join are elements of some universe *A*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Meanwhile, the arguments of the transformation group operations composition and inverse are elements of a set of bijections, *A* → *A*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Moving to groups in general, let *H* be a subgroup of some group *G*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Let ~ be an equivalence relation on *G*, such that $a\sim b{\text{ if and only if }}ab^{-1}\in H.$ The equivalence classes of ~—also called the orbits of the action of *H* on *G*—are the right **cosets** of *H* in *G*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Interchanging *a* and *b* yields the left cosets.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Related thinking can be found in Rosen (2008: chpt.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Let *G* be a set and let "~" denote an equivalence relation over *G*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Then we can form a groupoid representing this equivalence relation as follows.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The equivalence relations on any set *X*, when ordered by set inclusion, form a complete lattice, called **Con** *X* by convention.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] The canonical map **ker** : *X*^*X* → **Con** *X*, relates the monoid *X*^*X* of all functions on *X* and **Con** *X*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] **ker** is surjective but not injective.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Less formally, the equivalence relation **ker** on *X*, takes each function *f* : *X* → *X* to its kernel **ker** *f*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Likewise, **ker(ker)** is an equivalence relation on *X*^*X*.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] Equivalence relations are a ready source of examples or counterexamples.
[src:bisimulation/equivalence-relation] For example, an equivalence relation with exactly two infinite equivalence classes is an easy example of a theory which is ω-categorical, but not categorical for any larger cardinal number.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The language of propositional modal logic consists of a countably infinite set of propositional variables, a set of truth-functional connectives (in this article $\to$ and $\neg$ ), and the modal operator $\Box$ ("necessarily").
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The modal operator $\Diamond$ ("possibly") is (classically) the dual of $\Box$ and may be defined in terms of necessity like so: $\Diamond A:=\neg \Box \neg A$ ("possibly A" is defined as equivalent to "not necessarily not A").
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A **Kripke frame** or **modal frame** is a pair $\langle W,R\rangle$ , where *W* is a (possibly empty) set, and *R* is a binary relation on *W*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Elements of *W* are called *nodes* or *worlds*, and *R* is known as the accessibility relation.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] We read $w\Vdash A$ as “*w* satisfies *A*”, “*A* is satisfied in *w*”, or “*w* forces *A*”.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The relation $\Vdash$ is called the *satisfaction relation*, *evaluation*, or *forcing relation*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The satisfaction relation is uniquely determined by its value on propositional variables.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] We define Thm(*C*) to be the set of all formulas that are valid in *C*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Conversely, if *X* is a set of formulas, let Mod(*X*) be the class of all frames which validate every formula from *X*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A modal logic (i.e., a set of formulas) *L* is **sound** with respect to a class of frames *C*, if *L* ⊆ Thm(*C*).
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Semantics is useful for investigating a logic (i.e. a derivation system) only if the semantic consequence relation reflects its syntactical counterpart, the *syntactic consequence* relation (*derivability*).
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] It is vital to know which modal logics are sound and complete with respect to a class of Kripke frames, and to determine also which class that is.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] For any class *C* of Kripke frames, Thm(*C*) is a normal modal logic (in particular, theorems of the minimal normal modal logic, *K*, are valid in every Kripke model).
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] However, the converse does not hold in general: while most of the modal systems studied are complete of classes of frames described by simple conditions, Kripke incomplete normal modal logics do exist.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A natural example of such a system is Japaridze's polymodal logic.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A normal modal logic *L* **corresponds** to a class of frames *C*, if *C* = Mod(*L*).
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] In other words, *C* is the largest class of frames such that *L* is sound wrt *C*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] It follows that *L* is Kripke complete if and only if it is complete of its corresponding class.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Consider the schema **T** : $\Box A\to A$ .
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] **T** is valid in any reflexive frame $\langle W,R\rangle$ : if $w\Vdash \Box A$ , then $w\Vdash A$ since *w* *R* *w*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] On the other hand, a frame which validates **T** has to be reflexive: fix *w* ∈ *W*, and define satisfaction of a propositional variable *p* as follows: $u\Vdash p$ if and only if *w* *R* *u*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Then $w\Vdash \Box p$ , thus $w\Vdash p$ by **T**, which means *w* *R* *w* using the definition of $\Vdash$ .
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] **T** corresponds to the class of reflexive Kripke frames.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] It is often much easier to characterize the corresponding class of *L* than to prove its completeness, thus correspondence serves as a guide to completeness proofs.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Correspondence is also used to show *incompleteness* of modal logics: suppose *L*1 ⊆ *L*2 are normal modal logics that correspond to the same class of frames, but *L*1 does not prove all theorems of *L*2.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] For example, the schema $\Box (A\leftrightarrow \Box A)\to \Box A$ generates an incomplete logic, as it corresponds to the same class of frames as **GL** (viz. transitive and converse well-founded frames), but does not prove the **GL**-tautology $\Box A\to \Box \Box A$ .
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The following table lists common modal axioms together with their corresponding classes.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The naming of the axioms often varies; Here, axiom **K** is named after Saul Kripke; axiom **T** is named after the truth axiom in epistemic logic; axiom **D** is named after deontic logic; axiom **B** is named after L.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Brouwer; and axioms **4** and **5** are named based on C.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Lewis's numbering of symbolic logic systems.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Axiom **K** can also be rewritten as $\Box [(A\to B)\land A]\to \Box B$ , which logically establishes modus ponens as a rule of inference in every possible world.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Note that for axiom **D**, $\Diamond A$ implicitly implies $\Diamond \top$ , which means that for every possible world in the model, there is always at least one possible world accessible from it (which could be itself).
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] This implicit implication $\Diamond A\rightarrow \Diamond \top$ is similar to the implicit implication by existential quantifier on the range of quantification.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The following table lists several common normal modal systems.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Frame conditions for some of the systems were simplified: the logics are *sound and complete* with respect to the frame classes given in the table, but they may *correspond* to a larger class of frames.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] For any normal modal logic, *L*, a Kripke model (called the **canonical model**) can be constructed that refutes precisely the non-theorems of *L*, by an adaptation of the standard technique of using maximal consistent sets as models.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Canonical Kripke models play a role similar to the Lindenbaum–Tarski algebra construction in algebraic semantics.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A set of formulas is *L*-*consistent* if no contradiction can be derived from it using the theorems of *L*, and Modus Ponens.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A *maximal L-consistent set* (an *L*-*MCS* for short) is an *L*-consistent set that has no proper *L*-consistent superset.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The canonical model is a model of *L*, as every *L*-*MCS* contains all theorems of *L*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] By Zorn's lemma, each *L*-consistent set is contained in an *L*-*MCS*, in particular every formula unprovable in *L* has a counterexample in the canonical model.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The main application of canonical models are completeness proofs.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Properties of the canonical model of **K** immediately imply completeness of **K** with respect to the class of all Kripke frames.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] This argument does *not* work for arbitrary *L*, because there is no guarantee that the underlying *frame* of the canonical model satisfies the frame conditions of *L*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A union of canonical sets of formulas is itself canonical.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] It follows from the preceding discussion that any logic axiomatized by a canonical set of formulas is Kripke complete, and compact.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The axioms T, 4, D, B, 5, H, G (and thus any combination of them) are canonical.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] GL and Grz are not canonical, because they are not compact.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The axiom M by itself is not canonical (Goldblatt, 1991), but the combined logic **S4.1** (in fact, even **K4.1**) is canonical.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] In general, it is undecidable whether a given axiom is canonical.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] This is a powerful criterion: for example, all axioms listed above as canonical are (equivalent to) Sahlqvist formulas.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A logic has the **finite model property** (FMP) if it is complete with respect to a class of finite frames.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] An application of this notion is the decidability question: it follows from Post's theorem that a recursively axiomatized modal logic *L* which has FMP is decidable, provided it is decidable whether a given finite frame is a model of *L*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] In particular, every finitely axiomatizable logic with FMP is decidable.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] There are various methods for establishing FMP for a given logic.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Refinements and extensions of the canonical model construction often work, using tools such as filtration or unravelling.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] As another possibility, completeness proofs based on cut-free sequent calculi usually produce finite models directly.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Most of the modal systems used in practice (including all listed above) have FMP.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] In some cases, we can use FMP to prove Kripke completeness of a logic: every normal modal logic is complete with respect to a class of modal algebras, and a *finite* modal algebra can be transformed into a Kripke frame.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] As an example, Robert Bull proved using this method that every normal extension of **S4.3** has FMP, and is Kripke complete.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Kripke semantics has a straightforward generalization to logics with more than one modality.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A Kripke frame for a language with $\{\Box _{i}\mid \,i\in I\}$ as the set of its necessity operators consists of a non-empty set *W* equipped with binary relations *Ri* for each *i* ∈ *I*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A simplified semantics, discovered by Tim Carlson, is often used for polymodal provability logics.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] A **Carlson model** is a structure $\langle W,R,\{D_{i}\}_{i\in I},\Vdash \rangle$ with a single accessibility relation *R*, and subsets *Di* ⊆ *W* for each modality.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Carlson models are easier to visualize and to work with than usual polymodal Kripke models; there are, however, Kripke complete polymodal logics which are Carlson incomplete.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Kripke semantics for intuitionistic logic follows the same principles as the semantics of modal logic, but it uses a different definition of satisfaction.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Intuitively, the additional requirement for $w\Vdash A\to B$ is to ensure the monotinicity even for compound propositions, i.e., for any proposition *A*, if $w\leq u$ and $w\Vdash A$ , then $u\Vdash A$ .
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The negation of *A*, ¬*A*, could be defined as an abbreviation for *A* → ⊥.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Intuitionistic logic is sound and complete with respect to its Kripke semantics, and it has the finite model property.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Here *e*(*x*→*a*) is the evaluation which gives *x* the value *a*, and otherwise agrees with *e*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] As part of the independent development of sheaf theory, it was realised around 1965 that Kripke semantics was intimately related to the treatment of existential quantification in topos theory.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] That is, the 'local' aspect of existence for sections of a sheaf was a kind of logic of the 'possible'.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Though this development was the work of a number of people, the name **Kripke–Joyal** or simple **sheaf semantics** is often used in this connection.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] Sheaf semantics unifies Kripke and the similar Beth semantics, as well as extend it from the proof-irrelevant (propositional) to the proof relevant cases, in the case the accessibility relation R is reflexive and transitive.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] As in classical model theory, there are methods for constructing a new Kripke model from other models.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The natural homomorphisms in Kripke semantics are called **p-morphisms** (which is short for *pseudo-epimorphism*, but the latter term is rarely used).
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] P-morphisms are a special kind of bisimulations.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The key property which follows from this definition is that bisimulations (hence also p-morphisms) of models preserve the satisfaction of *all* formulas, not only propositional variables.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] We can transform a Kripke model into a tree using **unravelling**.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] but many applications need the reflexive and/or transitive closure of this relation, or similar modifications.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] It follows that *f* preserves satisfaction of all formulas from *X*.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] As in the case of unravelling, the definition of the accessibility relation on the quotient varies.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] The main defect of Kripke semantics is the existence of Kripke incomplete logics, and logics which are complete but not compact.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] It can be remedied by equipping Kripke frames with extra structure which restricts the set of possible valuations, using ideas from algebraic semantics.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] This gives rise to the general frame semantics.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] (2001) argue that, because a relational structure is simply a set together with a collection of relations on that set, it is unsurprising that relational structures can often be found.
[src:bisimulation/kripke-semantics] As an example from theoretical computer science, they give labeled transition systems, which model program execution.
[src:bisimulation/observational-equivalence] In econometrics, two parameter values (or two *structures,* from among a class of statistical models) are considered observationally equivalent if they both result in the same probability distribution of observable data.
[src:bisimulation/observational-equivalence] This term often arises in relation to the identification problem.
[src:bisimulation/observational-equivalence] In macroeconomics, it happens when you have multiple structural models, with different interpretation, but indistinguishable empirically.
[src:bisimulation/observational-equivalence] In the formal semantics of programming languages, two terms *M* and *N* are observationally equivalent if and only if, in all contexts *C*[...] where *C*[*M*] is a valid term, it is the case that *C*[*N*] is also a valid term with the same value.
[src:bisimulation/observational-equivalence] Thus it is not possible, within the system, to distinguish between the two terms.
[src:bisimulation/observational-equivalence] This definition can be made precise only with respect to a particular calculus, one that comes with its own specific definitions of *term*, *context*, and the *value of a term*.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] In theoretical computer science, a **simulation** is a relation between state transition systems associating systems that behave in the same way in the sense that one system *simulates* the other.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Intuitively, a system simulates another system if it can match all of its moves.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] The basic definition relates states within one transition system, but this is easily adapted to relate two separate transition systems by building a system consisting of the disjoint union of the corresponding components.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Given two states p and q in S , p can be **simulated** by q , written $p\,\leq \,q$ , if and only if there is a simulation R such that $(p,q)\in R$ .
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] The relation $\leq$ is called the **simulation preorder**, and it is the union of all simulations: $(p,q)\in \,\leq \,$ precisely when $(p,q)\in R$ for some simulation R .
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] The set of simulations is closed under union; therefore, the simulation preorder is itself a simulation.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Since it is the union of all simulations, it is the unique largest simulation.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Simulations are also closed under reflexive and transitive closure; therefore, the largest simulation must be reflexive and transitive.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] From this follows that the largest simulation—the simulation preorder—is indeed a preorder relation.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Note that there can be more than one relation that is both a simulation and a preorder; the term *simulation preorder* refers to the largest one of them (which is a superset of all the others).
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Two states p and q are said to be **similar**, written $p\leq \geq q$ , if and only if p can be simulated by q and q can be simulated by p .
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Similarity is thus the maximal symmetric subset of the simulation preorder, which means it is reflexive, symmetric, and transitive; hence an equivalence relation.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] However, it is not necessarily a simulation, and precisely in those cases when it is not a simulation, it is strictly coarser than bisimilarity (meaning it is a superset of bisimilarity).
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] To witness, consider a similarity that *is* a simulation.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Since it is symmetric, it is a *bisimulation*.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] It must then be a *subset* of bisimilarity, which is the union of all bisimulations.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Yet it is easy to see that similarity is always a *superset* of bisimilarity.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] From this follows that if similarity is a simulation, it equals bisimilarity.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] And if it equals bisimilarity, it is naturally a simulation (since bisimilarity is a simulation).
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] Therefore, similarity is a simulation if and only if it equals bisimilarity.
[src:bisimulation/simulation-preorder] If it does not, it must be its strict superset; hence a strictly coarser equivalence relation.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] In theoretical computer science, a **transition system** is a state machine that may have infinite states.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] It is used to describe the potential behavior of discrete systems.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] It consists of states and transitions between states, which may be labeled with labels chosen from a set; the same label may appear on more than one transition.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] If the label set is a singleton, the system is essentially unlabeled, and a simpler definition that omits the labels is possible.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Transition systems coincide mathematically with abstract rewriting systems (as explained further in this article) and directed graphs.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Transition systems can be represented as directed graphs.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Formally, a **transition system** is a pair $(S,T)$ where S is a set of states and T , the *transition relation*, is a subset of $S\times S$ .
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] We say that there is a transition from state p to state q if $(p,q)\in T$ , and denote it $p\rightarrow q$ .
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] A **labelled transition system** is a tuple $(S,\Lambda ,T)$ where S is a set of states, $\Lambda$ is a set of labels, and T , the *labelled transition relation*, is a subset of $S\times \Lambda \times S$ .
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Labels can represent different things depending on the language of interest.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Typical uses of labels include representing input expected, conditions that must be true to trigger the transition, or actions performed during the transition.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Labelled transitions systems were originally introduced as *named* transition systems.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] The formal definition can be rephrased as follows.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Labelled state transition systems on S with labels from $\Lambda$ correspond one-to-one with functions $S\to {\mathcal {P}}(\Lambda \times S)$ , where ${\mathcal {P}}$ is the (covariant) powerset functor.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] In other words, a labelled state transition system is a coalgebra for the functor $P(\Lambda \times {-})$ .
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] There are many relations between these concepts.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Some are simple, such as observing that a labelled transition system where the set of labels consists of only one element is equivalent to an unlabelled transition system.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] However, not all these relations are equally trivial.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] As a mathematical object, an unlabeled transition system is identical with an (unindexed) abstract rewriting system.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] If we consider the rewriting relation as an indexed set of relations, as some authors do, then a labeled transition system is equivalent to an abstract rewriting system with the indices being the labels.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] The focus of the study and the terminology are different, however.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] In a transition system one is interested in interpreting the labels as actions, whereas in an abstract rewriting system the focus is on how objects may be transformed (rewritten) into others.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] In model checking, a transition system is sometimes defined to include an additional labeling function for the states as well, resulting in a notion that encompasses that of Kripke structure.
[src:bisimulation/state-transition-system] Action languages are extensions of transition systems, adding a set of *fluents* *F*, a set of values *V*, and a function that maps *F* × *S* to *V*.
